    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_15439798" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/15439798" />
    <a title="Carole" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/392110-carole"><img alt="Carole" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/15439798?book_show_action=true">Feb 14, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Carole" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Carole" href="/user/show/392110-carole">Carole</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Everyone</span></div>

        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/392110-carole?shelf=thumpinggoodreads">thumpinggoodreads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/392110-carole?shelf=cantputitdown">cantputitdown</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer15439798" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5765707899403340879">I love this book! I am so glad I was reminded of it. This was first published in 1959, and The Literary Guild (my book club at the time) chose it as a monthly selection. I enjoyed it at the time, but I wasn&apos;t terribly interested in politics &apos;way back then so I really didn&apos;t get the bigger picture during that first read.<br/><br/>If you are into politics (and who isn&apos;t these days?) and especially if you&apos;d like to know how Congress -- the Senate in particular -- works, read this. It&apos;s a thumping good read i</span>
  <span id="freeText5765707899403340879" style="display:none">I love this book! I am so glad I was reminded of it. This was first published in 1959, and The Literary Guild (my book club at the time) chose it as a monthly selection. I enjoyed it at the time, but I wasn't terribly interested in politics 'way back then so I really didn't get the bigger picture during that first read.<br /><br />If you are into politics (and who isn't these days?) and especially if you'd like to know how Congress -- the Senate in particular -- works, read this. It's a thumping good read in the first place but is also recognized as still the best novel about our political system, our central government and Washington, D.C. It won the Pulitzer, was a smash hit Broadway play, and Otto Preminger made it into a movie.<br /><br />This is not an easy read. It's wordy and paragraphs are long. I had an English Lit teacher in college who told us that when reading Dickens, skip all paragraphs over ten lines long. Then if we enjoyed the story, go back and read every word to get the whole story. This book is like that.<br /><br />But, oh, what a story! Wonderful characters whom you will actually care about -- both the good guys and the bad ones. Great dialogue. Real and believable. A marvelous feel for location -- you'll find yourselves right there while these events are unfolding. And an absolutely Cracker Jack story. I could hardly wait to get to the end and then was stunned to realize that there was no more. I wanted more!<br /><br />I came back to this book because I had read a column in the Wall Street Journal many months ago by a columnist named Terry Teachout. He and some of his friends were brainstorming a list of written literature to give to people in the Middle East to teach them about this country, how it came to be, and its political system. I clipped that column out and began to try to find several of the books. This was one of them, and I finally found a paperback version at Amazon.com. The paperback cost me $15.00 from a rare book dealer, and the price on the front cover is $1.25. Oh, how times havae changed!<br /><br />The story is about four Senators in particular and their struggles over a Presidential nominee for Secretary of State. There is a huge "supporting cast," and its easy to get lost in all the names, but this is just a fabulous book that is wonderful on several different levels. I can't recommend is highly enough.<br /> </span>
  <a data-text-id="5765707899403340879" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

