    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2709089207" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2709089207" />
    <a title="Fred R" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2381925-fred-r"><img alt="Fred R" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2709089207?book_show_action=true">Feb 09, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Fred R" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Fred R" href="/user/show/2381925-fred-r">Fred R</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2709089207" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18062419888882549854">It opens slow, and for a while it seems like all you&apos;re going to get is period detail from a reporter&apos;s notebook, smothered in the shallow ironies and shallow profundities of a mid-century American man of the world. And then before you know it you&apos;re in the grip of a powerful political drama, an intelligent reshuffling early Cold War controversies (Hiss, McCarthy).<br/><br/>The president appears to be a Nixonian figure avant-l&apos;homme, pursuing detente with an ascendant Soviet Union but whatever political c</span>
  <span id="freeText18062419888882549854" style="display:none">It opens slow, and for a while it seems like all you're going to get is period detail from a reporter's notebook, smothered in the shallow ironies and shallow profundities of a mid-century American man of the world. And then before you know it you're in the grip of a powerful political drama, an intelligent reshuffling early Cold War controversies (Hiss, McCarthy).<br /><br />The president appears to be a Nixonian figure avant-l'homme, pursuing detente with an ascendant Soviet Union but whatever political chicanery necessary. Of course if that is his purpose left-liberal squish Leffingwell is horribly miscast for the role of a tough-minded Kissinger, which makes the whole motor of the plot (the ailing president's implacable desire to see Leffingwell confirmed as Secretary of State, despite his scandalous Communist background) somewhat puzzling.<br /><br />Ultimately, Drury's vital center sensibilities don't quite capture the essence of the drama involved with the Hiss Case, the Cold War, or political divides involved that still haunt us. To him this is mostly a story about who does and who does not behave like a gentleman in politics. To be sure he would prescribe a robust defense of the free world against Soviet aggression (and gets in some fairly cheap shots at a left-wing tendency to give up the struggle), but he simply doesn't recognize there were and are issues of treason, of loyalty to the nation, involved in this time and this place. Read Chambers' Witness. The fact of the matter is that Hiss was only an early harbinger of an elite tendency towards an oppositional and even revolutionary attitude towards the society it purportedly leads.<br /><br />Also, and as I understand more than one editor made clear, this book should really only be half as long as it is.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18062419888882549854" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


